# How to Save the World in Six Easy Steps

## A Business Plan for Liana Banyan Corporation

*Not left or right. A more effective team.*

---

*A little girl told her mother she wanted to be an astronaut.*

*Her mother, trying to be helpful, said: "Well, sweetheart, you'll need advanced college degrees. You'll need to serve in the military and get piloting hours. And then three years of experience leading others."*

*The girl looked at her mom and shrugged.*

*"No problem! That's just, like, three things."*

---

Figure out how to end World Hunger. Tell Everyone. And give them a selfish reason to do it.

That is, in full, the business plan. What follows is the machinery.

The selfish reason is not charity. It is not an appeal to conscience. It is mathematics. When you can pick apples and your neighbor can deliver them, and the platform pays each of you fairly -- Creators AND Workers keep **83.3%** of every transaction, every time, locked by constitutional bylaw -- cooperation becomes the rational choice. Not the noble choice. The *smart* choice.

That is the insight the cooperative economy has been waiting for. Not a better appeal to altruism. A better deal.

This is a business plan with six steps. Each step is a self-contained economic engine that feeds the next. Each step starts with one person doing one thing in one place. Each step scales without permission, without venture capital, and without anyone's approval but the people doing the work.

If you are looking for a pitch deck, this is not one. If you are looking for a fundraising ask, there is exactly one letter for that and it went to Warren Buffett. If you are looking for the catch -- the hidden fee, the equity trap, the extraction mechanism buried in the fine print -- you will not find one. We engineered it out.

What you will find instead is a cooperative commerce platform built from a six-month pivot out of a hydraulic gaming platform project -- when the Founder saw the real need, dropped the original plan, and shipped. The result: **2,270 documented innovations**, **21 USPTO provisional patent applications** protecting **2,270 formal patent claims**, **36 live production systems**, and a three-currency economic system with mathematical solvency proofs.

Built by one veteran, four AI agents, and nine years of obsession.

That is just, like, six things.

---

## Before We Start: The Economics

Every step runs on the same engine.

**Cost+20%.** That is the platform margin. Not "up to" -- exactly. Locked in the operating agreement. No board vote, no investor pressure, no quarterly earnings call can change it. **Creators AND Workers keep 83.3%** of every transaction. The platform takes what it needs to operate and nothing more.

**Three currencies.** Credits ($1 = 1 Credit, one-way valve, never cash out to fiat). Marks (effort-differential -- what you DID matters, not just what you paid). Joules (surplus stored value, like forever stamps). All at permanent parity. None of them are securities. They are participation instruments.

**$5/year membership.** That is the stake. That is all you can lose. Start a business, join an initiative, access the cooperative. Five dollars a year for life if you sign up before launch.

**500 members = break-even. 1,000 = profitable.** In any locale. The math works because the margin is fixed, the costs are known, and the demand is validated before production begins.

**50-year charter dissipation.** The cooperative does not flip in three years. It is structured to outlast the Founder.

**SSPL license + Cooperative Defensive Patent Pledge #2260.** The code is open. The patents are pledged defensively. No extraction mechanism can be buried in either.

The math IS the selfish reason. That is the point. When cooperation always pays fairly and transparently, self-interest and the common good stop being opposites. They align. We call this the Economic Rule of InterDependence -- the rule the entire architecture is designed to prove.

---

## Step 1: Level the Field

**What it is:** A shared memory layer that makes every AI dramatically more accurate on cooperative knowledge tasks.

**Why it is first:** Without a shared substrate, steps 2 through 6 are coordination problems that drain resources. Mnemosyne is the force multiplier that makes every subsequent step cheaper to run and easier to replicate in any locale.

**The origin:** MnemosyneC began as a Romulator -- a ROM+emulator system with a HAL-9000 substrate, first session October 9, 2025. Provisional #13 filed April 12, 2026. It is the genesis strain of the shared memory architecture.

**The rung doctrine:** MnemosyneC is a rung, not the destination. The destination is cooperation at scale. Sell the ladder.

The biggest cost in deploying AI today is not the model. It is the context -- rebuilding state from scratch on every call, re-reading the same documents, reconstructing the same understanding, paying for the same tokens again and again. Mnemosyne is the cooperative's answer to that waste.

When one AI resolves a question and deposits the answer into the substrate, every other AI that asks the same question gets the answer back for free -- or close to it. The work is done once. The benefit accumulates. The substrate compounds. This is what "cooperative" means at the infrastructure layer: we do not each build our own memory. We share one.

### The Sound Barrier -- what we measured

We set out to find a result that is empirically honest about what the substrate does and what it does not do yet.

**BP074 result:** Gemma 4 12B + LianaBanyan substrate scored **100% (25/25)**, Banyan Metric **90.45**, kappa **1.000**, **$0 marginal cost per query** once the substrate is populated.

**Honest disclosures (Truth-Always):**
- **L08 (ceiling effect):** 25-question set is small enough that a 100% score may reflect ceiling. We do not claim this generalizes to all question types without further testing.
- **L09 (num_predict):** The baseline run used num_predict=100 (truncated responses). The substrate run used num_predict=2048 (full responses). The accuracy improvement reflects both the substrate AND the longer generation window. We do not separate these effects and do not overclaim the substrate alone.
- **L10 (PENDING):** MMLU-Pro 1,000-question + GPQA Diamond 198-question 4-condition matrix is in progress. Phase 1.5 fired. Results within days. We will publish those numbers when they land.

**Mesh proof (proven, not pending):** A two-machine LAN test ran 20/20 hash-verified cross-node queries. Machine 1 held no local copy of Machine 2's data. Accuracy went from **0% to 100%** when the mesh was engaged. p50 16.6ms / p95 25.8ms. $0 LAN transport cost. The network-effect proof -- more of us is better -- is empirical, not theoretical.

**Why it matters for the six steps:** Every step below runs AI coordination. Every step gets this substrate for free once it is deployed in a locale. The infrastructure cost does not multiply per step -- it is shared.

**Designed to be copied.** Every installation is autonomous. The canonical URL is the only dependency. No flash drives. A Node of Socceri in San Antonio and a Node of Socceri in Nairobi hold the same substrate. The Frontier is the resilient mesh of all of them.

---

## Step 2: Feed Your Neighbors

**Cold Start: Food**
**Initiatives: Let's Make Dinner (#1) · Let's Get Groceries (#2) · The Family Table (#5) · Let's Make Bread (#11)**

We say Feed Your Neighbors First because that is the honest framing. The horizon is universal -- Feed Everyone -- but every network starts local.

A restaurant owner in San Antonio lists her menu on the platform. A neighbor photographs the food. A delivery driver brings breakfast tacos to the office park down the road. The cook keeps 83.3%. The photographer earns Marks. The driver accumulates toward vehicle ownership through the Earn-Down program. The office worker gets fresh food at her desk.

Nobody was rescued. Everybody benefited.

This is how the Great Depression was survived before there were safety nets: pick and deliver apples. Someone has something. Someone needs it. Someone does the work. The platform is the fair agreement between them -- without venture capital extracting the margin, without a platform fee that does not leave room to live.

**Let's Make Dinner** is neighbors feeding neighbors -- a cooperative meal coordination system where families sign up to cook for each other on rotating schedules. **The Family Table** (#5) connects through the cookbook system. **Let's Get Groceries** (#2) is cooperative purchasing: when 12 families buy flour together, they pay wholesale. **Let's Make Bread** (#11) is the industrial extension -- cooperative food production at scale.

**Why this is Step 2:** Food is the universal need. It is the first node in every economic network. When the first real dollar flows through the Commerce Engine, everything else becomes possible.

---

## Step 3: Employ the World

**Cold Start: Work**
**Initiatives: Let's Go Shopping (#3) · Household Concierge (#4) · Defense Klaus (#8) · Rally Group (#9)**

Everyone has something useful to do. The problem is not a shortage of work -- it is a shortage of fair arrangements for doing it.

**Rally Group** (#9) is community resilience made operational. When a wildfire hits a neighborhood, before FEMA arrives, the Rally Group has already dispatched a Crew Call -- local members with trucks, chainsaws, and first aid kits are on-site in hours. They earn Marks for their contribution. The community does not wait for someone else to save them. They save each other.

**Defense Klaus** (#8) is personal safety and legal defense -- for workers, by the cooperative. In January 2026, KSAT News documented the practice San Antonians call "Hood Uber" -- informal, unregulated peer ridesharing arranged through Facebook groups: no app, no permits, no commercial insurance, cash paid upfront, no background checks. A driver was shot when a passenger refused to pay the fare. The demand for affordable community transportation is proven. Defense Klaus provides the infrastructure to make it safe: payment processed before the trip, tiered background verification with community vouching, the Earn-Down vehicle ownership program, panic buttons, and legal defense for drivers working alone.

**Let's Go Shopping** (#3) and **Household Concierge** (#4) are the service economy made cooperative: errands, delivery, home services -- all at Cost+20%, all with Creators AND Workers keeping 83.3%.

**Why this is Step 3:** Once food is flowing, the next universal need is a productive livelihood. Employment is not just income -- it is dignity, identity, and membership in the economy.

---

## Step 4: Build Businesses and Make Things

**Cold Start: Local Business**
**Initiatives: VSL (#10) · Brass Tacks (#16)**
**System: $5 Incubator + Cue Card + Treasure Map + Captain + Business**

Anyone can try any venture for $5. A new member browses the 8 Treasure Maps -- each one a different business category with demand signals on the front and a mini business plan on the back. The Cold Start Hub walks her through registration, first Cue Card, first customers. The Captain System kicks in at 20 orders.

**VSL** (#10) is the video sales letter engine -- cooperative marketing infrastructure that any member can run without a marketing budget. **Brass Tacks** (#16) is the operations and systems layer -- the paperwork, the back-office, the compliance structure that makes a side hustle into a legitimate business.

**Why this is Step 4:** Employment (Step 3) gives people a job. Business ownership gives them a stake. These are different things. The cooperative is designed to produce both -- first work, then ownership.

---

## Step 5: Power to the People

**Cold Start: Civic**
**Initiatives: Power to the People (#15) · Tatiana Schlossberg Health Accords (#6) · MSA / Tereno (#7)**

*Not left or right. A more effective team.*

This is the Switzerland step.

By the time a community has shared food, shared work, shared ownership, and shared infrastructure, it has also built the legitimacy to share governance. Step 5 is where that legitimacy becomes structural.

**Political Expedition** (Initiative #15) is the civic-action arm: nonpartisan civic transparency, accountability tools, the machinery of representative self-governance built by the people it governs. It does not import ideology. It exports the structure that lets communities make their own choices, fairly. What do the facts say? What will we do together?

**The Orchard** is the civic-discourse arm -- a separate spinout-class entity where reason and faith and politics can meet across difference, judged by truth rather than tribal membership. Fruit is judged by the fruit, not the tree it fell from. You can bring any worldview. You must bring your evidence.

**Tatiana Schlossberg Health Accords** (#6) and **MSA/Tereno** (#7) are the policy and structural arms -- health access at Cost+20% and regional economic organization that gives communities collective negotiating weight.

**Why this is Step 5:** Power must be earned, not seized. A community that has fed itself, employed itself, and built its own businesses has earned the right to govern itself.

---

## Step 6: Belong Together

**Cold Start: Tribe**
**Initiatives: The Muses (Guild) · JukeBox (#13) · Didasko (#14)**

A Tribe is a personal group. Your neighborhood. Your faith community. Your running club. Many Tribes per member.

A Guild (Step 3) is professional -- what you DO. A Tribe is personal -- who you ARE.

**The Muses** is the creative-community layer -- the guild for every starving artist who is done starving: artists, writers, musicians, and storytellers finding their people (the daughters of Mnemosyne; Banyan Galleries is its home). **JukeBox** (#13) is the music and cultural-expression arm -- a cooperative performance and distribution layer that puts Creators AND Workers first. **Didasko** (#14) is the learning and teaching arm -- the cooperative where knowledge passes from those who have it to those who need it, at Cost+20%, with the teacher keeping 83.3%.

Belonging is the sixth step because it is the hardest to engineer and the last to arrive -- but when it arrives, it is the one that makes everything else sustainable. People do not fight for platforms. They fight for communities. The platform is the substrate. The community is the point.

**Why this is Step 6:** The staircase goes: tool -> sustenance -> livelihood -> enterprise -> power -> belonging. Each step makes the next reachable. None extracts from the others. That non-extractive, mutually-enabling ladder is the Economic Rule of InterDependence rendered concrete.

---

## The Economic Proof: Why Cooperation Is the Selfish Reason

This is not a charity. The thesis of this paper is a mathematical claim.

**Claim:** It is universally worthwhile to cooperate inside a system where every participant receives a fair return.

**The three pillars:**

**1. Equate all world currencies inside Liana Banyan.** The three-gear currency system (Credits, Marks, Joules) with purchasing-power parity baked into the platform margin makes "universal" literal. A Credit is a Credit whether earned in San Antonio or Lagos. The platform does not extract from the differential between what you earn and what things cost where you live. It closes it.

**2. "Pick and deliver apples."** In the Great Depression, people found ways to survive by doing work that was real and needed -- without venture capital, without institutional approval, with nothing but a fair agreement between a person with something to offer and a person who needed it. The cooperative replicates that logic at scale: anyone can sign up to do real work; receivers reciprocate in kind. Without VC, but NEVER without a fair share. Cost+20%. 83.3% kept. The Tab System mathematical solvency proof (sum of all satisfied requests times revenue per request is greater than or equal to total expenses) ensures the platform cannot go insolvent while paying everyone fairly.

**3. The selfish reason.** When cooperation always pays fairly and transparently, self-interest and the common good stop being opposites. They align. You do not need to be a saint to join this platform. You need to see that the math works in your favor. It does. The math IS the selfish reason.

